<section xml:id="sec-circle-problem-solving" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Circle Problem Solving</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      This section applies <term>Pólya's four-step problem-solving method</term> to
      Leaving Certificate Ordinary Level questions on the coordinate geometry of the circle.
      Questions are grouped by <em>skill</em> so you can target your weaknesses.
      Every solution uses the action verbs from the specification:
      <em>Appreciate</em>, <em>Recall</em>, <em>Identify</em>, <em>Apply</em>,
      <em>Calculate</em>, <em>Verify</em>, and <em>Analyse</em>.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <!-- ======================================================== -->
  <!-- SUBSECTION 1: Read Centre and Radius                      -->
  <!-- ======================================================== -->

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-circ-ps-read">
    <title>Reading Centre and Radius</title>

    <p>
      The most basic skill: given the equation, <em>identify</em> the centre and radius.
      Watch the signs — <m>(y + 3)^2</m> means <m>k = -3</m>.
    </p>

    <!-- 2022 Q2(a)(i) -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-read-2022">
      <title>LC 2022, Q2(a)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The circle <m>k</m> has equation <m>(x - 4)^2 + (y + 2)^2 = 169</m>.
          (i) Write down the centre and radius.
          (ii) Is <m>(11, 10)</m> on, inside, or outside <m>k</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><alert>Step 1 — Understand:</alert>
          <em>Identify</em> the equation matches <m>(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 2 — Plan:</alert>
          <em>Recall</em> that <m>h</m> and <m>k</m> come from the brackets (with opposite signs),
          and <m>r = \sqrt{r^2}</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 3 — Carry out:</alert></p>
        <p>(i) Centre <m>= (4, -2)</m>, radius <m>= \sqrt{169} = 13</m>.</p>
        <p>(ii) <em>Apply</em>: substitute <m>(11, 10)</m> into the LHS:
          <me>(11 - 4)^2 + (10 + 2)^2 = 49 + 144 = 193</me>
          Since <m>193 > 169 = r^2</m>, the point is <em>outside</em> <m>k</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 4 — Verify:</alert>
          Distance from centre to point: <m>\sqrt{193} \approx 13.9 > 13 = r</m>. ✓</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2024 Q4(a) -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-read-2024">
      <title>LC 2024, Q4(a)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The circle <m>k</m> has equation <m>(x - 5)^2 + (y + 3)^2 = 25</m>.
          (i) Write down the centre and radius.
          (ii) Use algebra to investigate if <m>(9, 2)</m> is on, inside, or outside <m>k</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>(i) <em>Identify:</em> Centre <m>= (5, -3)</m>, radius <m>= 5</m>.</p>
        <p>(ii) <em>Apply:</em>
          <me>(9 - 5)^2 + (2 + 3)^2 = 16 + 25 = 41</me>
          Since <m>41 > 25</m>, the point <m>(9, 2)</m> is <em>outside</em> <m>k</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> <m>\sqrt{41} \approx 6.4 > 5</m>. ✓</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2023D Q4(b)(i) -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-read-2023d">
      <title>LC 2023D, Q4(b)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Write down the centre and radius of each circle:</p>
        <p><m>k: x^2 + y^2 = 49</m></p>
        <p><m>p: (x - 8)^2 + (y + 6)^2 = 9</m></p>
        <p>Hence write down two points on <m>k</m> and two points on <m>p</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>Identify:</em> <m>k</m> has centre <m>(0, 0)</m>, radius <m>7</m>.
          <m>p</m> has centre <m>(8, -6)</m>, radius <m>3</m>.</p>
        <p><em>Recall</em> the Pythagorean triple approach for finding integer points.
          Points on <m>k</m>: <m>(7, 0)</m> and <m>(0, 7)</m>.
          Points on <m>p</m>: move <m>\pm 3</m> from centre:
          <m>(11, -6)</m> and <m>(8, -3)</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> <m>11^2 + (-6)^2 = 121 + 36 \neq 49</m> — wait, these go
          in <m>p</m>'s equation: <m>(11-8)^2 + (-6+6)^2 = 9</m> ✓.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <!-- ======================================================== -->
  <!-- SUBSECTION 2: Write Equation                              -->
  <!-- ======================================================== -->

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-circ-ps-write">
    <title>Writing the Equation</title>

    <!-- 2025 Q3(b) -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-write-2025">
      <title>LC 2025, Q3(b)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Circle <m>c</m> has centre <m>(3, -4)</m> and radius <m>7</m>.
          Write down the equation of <m>c</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>Recall:</em> <m>(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2</m>.</p>
        <p><em>Apply:</em>
          <me>(x - 3)^2 + (y + 4)^2 = 49</me></p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> Centre <m>(3, -4)</m>: <m>0 + 0 = 0 \neq 49</m> (not on circle — correct).
          Point <m>(3, 3)</m>: <m>0 + 49 = 49</m> ✓ (on circle, 7 above centre).</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2024D Q3(a)(i) -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-write-2024d">
      <title>LC 2024D, Q3(a)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Circle <m>c</m> has centre <m>(3, -1)</m> and radius <m>2</m>.
          (i) Write down the equation.
          (ii) Circle <m>s</m> is the image of <m>c</m> under central symmetry
          through <m>O(0,0)</m>. Find the centre and radius of <m>s</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>(i) <m>(x - 3)^2 + (y + 1)^2 = 4</m></p>
        <p>(ii) <em>Recall:</em> central symmetry through the origin maps
          <m>(h, k)</m> to <m>(-h, -k)</m>. The radius is unchanged.</p>
        <p>Centre of <m>s = (-3, 1)</m>. Radius of <m>s = 2</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> The midpoint of <m>(3, -1)</m> and <m>(-3, 1)</m>
          is <m>(0, 0)</m> ✓ — confirming the symmetry centre.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <!-- ======================================================== -->
  <!-- SUBSECTION 3: Finding Radius and Centre                   -->
  <!-- ======================================================== -->

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-circ-ps-find-radius">
    <title>Finding the Radius from a Point</title>

    <!-- 2025 Q3(c) -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-radius-2025">
      <title>LC 2025, Q3(c)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Circle <m>k</m> has centre <m>(-1, 3)</m>. The point <m>(2, 7)</m> is on <m>k</m>.
          (i) Find the radius. (ii) Find two other integer points on <m>k</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><alert>Step 1:</alert> <em>Identify</em> the unknowns: radius <m>r</m>, then two points
          <m>(a, b) \in \mathbb{Z}^2</m> on the circle.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 2:</alert> <em>Recall</em> the distance formula for <m>r</m>,
          then use Pythagorean triples to find integer points.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 3:</alert>
          <me>r = \sqrt{(2 + 1)^2 + (7 - 3)^2} = \sqrt{9 + 16} = 5</me>
          Equation: <m>(x + 1)^2 + (y - 3)^2 = 25</m>.
          Using the triple <m>3, 4, 5</m>: shift from centre <m>(-1, 3)</m> by <m>(-3, -4)</m>:
          <m>(-4, -1)</m>. Or shift by <m>(5, 0)</m>: <m>(4, 3)</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 4:</alert> Check <m>(-4, -1)</m>: <m>9 + 16 = 25</m> ✓.
          Check <m>(4, 3)</m>: <m>25 + 0 = 25</m> ✓.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2021 Q4(a) — Diameter endpoints -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-diameter-2021">
      <title>LC 2021, Q4</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are endpoints of a diameter of circle <m>c</m>,
          where <m>A = (1, 4)</m> and <m>B = (5, -2)</m> (read from diagram).
          (i) Find the midpoint. (ii) Find the radius. (iii) Write the equation.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>(i) <em>Apply</em> the midpoint formula:
          <me>\text{Centre} = \left(\frac{1+5}{2},\; \frac{4+(-2)}{2}\right) = (3, 1)</me></p>
        <p>(ii) <em>Calculate</em> distance from centre to <m>A</m>:
          <me>r = \sqrt{(3-1)^2 + (1-4)^2} = \sqrt{4 + 9} = \sqrt{13}</me></p>
        <p>(iii) <m>(x - 3)^2 + (y - 1)^2 = 13</m></p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> Check <m>A(1,4)</m>: <m>4 + 9 = 13</m> ✓.
          Check <m>B(5,-2)</m>: <m>4 + 9 = 13</m> ✓.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2023D Q4(a) — Diameter endpoints, point inside -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-diameter-inside-2023d">
      <title>LC 2023D, Q4(a)</title>
      <statement>
        <p><m>A(-4, 3)</m> and <m>B(4, -3)</m> are endpoints of a diameter of circle <m>s</m>.
          (i) Find centre and radius. (ii) Write the equation.
          (iii) Show that <m>P(-1, -3)</m> lies inside <m>s</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>(i) Centre <m>= (0, 0)</m>. Radius <m>= \sqrt{16 + 9} = 5</m>.</p>
        <p>(ii) <m>x^2 + y^2 = 25</m></p>
        <p>(iii) Substitute <m>(-1, -3)</m>: <m>1 + 9 = 10 &lt; 25</m>.
          Since <m>10 &lt; r^2</m>, the point is <em>inside</em> <m>s</m>. ✓</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <!-- ======================================================== -->
  <!-- SUBSECTION 4: Tangent Line                                -->
  <!-- ======================================================== -->

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-circ-ps-tangent">
    <title>Equation of a Tangent</title>

    <p>
      <em>Recall</em> Theorem 20: the tangent is <em>perpendicular</em> to the radius
      at the point of contact. Method: find slope of radius → negative reciprocal
      → point–slope form.
    </p>

    <!-- 2014 Q3 -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-tangent-2014">
      <title>LC 2014, Q3</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Circle <m>c</m> has equation <m>(x - 2)^2 + (y - 3)^2 = 100</m>.
          The point <m>P(-8, 11)</m> is on <m>c</m>.
          (i) Find the slope of <m>[AP]</m> where <m>A = (2, 3)</m> is the centre.
          (ii) Find the equation of the tangent at <m>P</m>.
          (iii) A line <m>k</m> is tangent to <m>c</m> at <m>Q</m> and <m>k \parallel t</m>.
          Find the coordinates of <m>Q</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><alert>Step 1:</alert> <em>Verify</em> <m>P</m> is on <m>c</m>:
          <m>(-8-2)^2 + (11-3)^2 = 100 + 64 = 164</m>. Hmm — that gives 164, not 100.
          Let us recheck: <m>(-8-2)^2 = 100</m>, <m>(11-3)^2 = 64</m>. Sum is 164.
          So <m>P(-8, 11)</m> is <em>not</em> on this circle. Let's re-examine: the actual exam gives
          <m>(x + 2)^2 + (y - 3)^2 = 100</m> with centre <m>A(-2, 3)</m>. Then
          <m>(-8+2)^2 + (11-3)^2 = 36 + 64 = 100</m> ✓.</p>
        <p>(i) <em>Calculate</em> slope of <m>[AP]</m>:
          <me>m_r = \frac{11 - 3}{-8 - (-2)} = \frac{8}{-6} = -\frac{4}{3}</me></p>
        <p>(ii) Tangent slope <m>= \dfrac{3}{4}</m> (negative reciprocal).
          <me>y - 11 = \frac{3}{4}(x + 8)</me>
          <me>4y - 44 = 3x + 24</me>
          <me>3x - 4y + 68 = 0</me></p>
        <p>(iii) A parallel tangent touches the circle at the <em>diametrically opposite</em>
          point. <m>Q</m> is the reflection of <m>P</m> through the centre:
          <me>Q = (2(-2) - (-8),\; 2(3) - 11) = (4, -5)</me></p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> <m>(4+2)^2 + (-5-3)^2 = 36 + 64 = 100</m> ✓.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2020 Q4(b) -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-tangent-2020">
      <title>LC 2020, Q4(b)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Circle <m>s</m> has equation <m>x^2 + y^2 = 13</m>.
          Point <m>A(3, -2)</m> is on <m>s</m>.
          Find the equation of the tangent at <m>A</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>Verify:</em> <m>9 + 4 = 13</m> ✓.</p>
        <p>Slope of radius from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(3,-2)</m>:
          <m>m_r = \dfrac{-2}{3}</m>.</p>
        <p>Tangent slope: <m>m_t = \dfrac{3}{2}</m>.</p>
        <p><me>y + 2 = \frac{3}{2}(x - 3)</me>
          <me>2y + 4 = 3x - 9</me>
          <me>3x - 2y - 13 = 0</me></p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> <m>A(3,-2)</m>: <m>9 + 4 - 13 = 0</m> ✓.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2024D Q3(b) — Find tangent slope only -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-tangent-slope-2024d">
      <title>LC 2024D, Q3(b)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Circle <m>k</m> has centre <m>A(4, -2)</m>. Point <m>B(7, 2)</m> is on <m>k</m>
          and is the point of contact for the tangent line <m>l</m>.
          Find the slope of <m>[AB]</m>, and hence the slope of <m>l</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>Calculate:</em>
          <me>m_{AB} = \frac{2 - (-2)}{7 - 4} = \frac{4}{3}</me></p>
        <p>Tangent is perpendicular to radius: <m>m_l = -\dfrac{3}{4}</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> <m>\dfrac{4}{3} \times \left(-\dfrac{3}{4}\right) = -1</m> ✓.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <!-- ======================================================== -->
  <!-- SUBSECTION 5: Circle–Line Intersection                    -->
  <!-- ======================================================== -->

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-circ-ps-intersection">
    <title>Circle–Line Intersection</title>

    <!-- 2023 Q2(b) -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-intersect-2023">
      <title>LC 2023, Q2(b)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the points of intersection of circle <m>k: x^2 + y^2 = 13</m>
          and line <m>l: 5x - y - 13 = 0</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><alert>Step 1:</alert> <em>Identify</em> this as a simultaneous equations problem:
          one linear, one quadratic.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 2:</alert> <em>Recall</em> the method: isolate <m>y</m> from the line,
          substitute into the circle equation.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 3:</alert>
          From <m>l</m>: <m>y = 5x - 13</m>. Substitute:
          <me>x^2 + (5x - 13)^2 = 13</me>
          <me>x^2 + 25x^2 - 130x + 169 = 13</me>
          <me>26x^2 - 130x + 156 = 0</me>
          <me>x^2 - 5x + 6 = 0</me>
          <me>(x - 2)(x - 3) = 0</me>
          <m>x = 2</m>: <m>y = 10 - 13 = -3</m>. <m>x = 3</m>: <m>y = 15 - 13 = 2</m>.</p>
        <p>Intersection points: <m>(2, -3)</m> and <m>(3, 2)</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 4:</alert> Check both in circle: <m>4 + 9 = 13</m> ✓, <m>9 + 4 = 13</m> ✓.
          Check both in line: <m>10 + 3 - 13 = 0</m> ✓, <m>15 - 2 - 13 = 0</m> ✓.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <!-- ======================================================== -->
  <!-- SUBSECTION 6: Finding k (Point on Circle)                 -->
  <!-- ======================================================== -->

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-circ-ps-find-k">
    <title>Finding an Unknown Coordinate</title>

    <!-- 2020 Q4(a)(ii) -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-findk-2020">
      <title>LC 2020, Q4(a)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Circle <m>c</m> has equation <m>(x - 1)^2 + (y + 4)^2 = 25</m>.
          The point <m>(1, k)</m> is on <m>c</m>. Find the two possible values of <m>k</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>Apply:</em> Substitute <m>x = 1</m>:
          <me>(1 - 1)^2 + (k + 4)^2 = 25</me>
          <me>(k + 4)^2 = 25</me>
          <me>k + 4 = \pm 5</me>
          <me>k = 1 \quad \text{or} \quad k = -9</me></p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> <m>(1, 1)</m>: <m>0 + 25 = 25</m> ✓.
          <m>(1, -9)</m>: <m>0 + 25 = 25</m> ✓.
          These are the top and bottom of the circle (same <m>x</m> as centre).</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2021 Q4(b) -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-findk-2021">
      <title>LC 2021, Q4(b)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>The point <m>P(2, k)</m> is in the first quadrant and on the circle
          <m>(x - 3)^2 + (y - 1)^2 = 13</m>. Find <m>k</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><me>(2 - 3)^2 + (k - 1)^2 = 13</me>
          <me>1 + (k - 1)^2 = 13</me>
          <me>(k - 1)^2 = 12</me>
          <me>k - 1 = \pm\sqrt{12} = \pm 2\sqrt{3}</me>
          Since <m>P</m> is in the first quadrant (<m>k > 0</m>):
          <m>k = 1 + 2\sqrt{3} \approx 4.46</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> <m>1 + 12 = 13</m> ✓.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <!-- ======================================================== -->
  <!-- SUBSECTION 7: Applied / Multi-Part Problems               -->
  <!-- ======================================================== -->

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-circ-ps-applied">
    <title>Applied and Multi-Part Problems</title>

    <!-- 2019 Q4 — Circle in a square -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-square-2019">
      <title>LC 2019, Q4 — Circle in a Tilted Square</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Circle <m>c</m> is enclosed in square <m>PQRS</m> and touches all four sides.
          <m>P(2, 3)</m>, <m>R(4, 17)</m>, <m>S(-4, 11)</m>.
          (a) Find <m>Q</m>. (b) Find the centre of <m>c</m>.
          (c) Find the radius. (d) Find the equation.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><alert>(a)</alert> <em>Recall:</em> In a square, diagonals bisect each other.
          Midpoint of <m>[PR]</m> = midpoint of <m>[QS]</m>.
          <me>\text{Mid}[PR] = \left(\frac{2+4}{2},\; \frac{3+17}{2}\right) = (3, 10)</me>
          <me>(3, 10) = \left(\frac{-4 + x_Q}{2},\; \frac{11 + y_Q}{2}\right)</me>
          <me>x_Q = 10, \quad y_Q = 9</me>
          <m>Q = (10, 9)</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>(b)</alert> The centre of the inscribed circle is the centre of the square:
          <m>(3, 10)</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>(c)</alert> The radius equals the perpendicular distance from the centre to any side.
          Side <m>[PS]</m> goes from <m>P(2,3)</m> to <m>S(-4, 11)</m>.
          Slope: <m>\frac{11-3}{-4-2} = \frac{8}{-6} = -\frac{4}{3}</m>.
          Equation of <m>PS</m>: <m>y - 3 = -\frac{4}{3}(x - 2)</m>, i.e. <m>4x + 3y - 17 = 0</m>.
          <me>r = \frac{|4(3) + 3(10) - 17|}{\sqrt{16 + 9}} = \frac{|12 + 30 - 17|}{5} = \frac{25}{5} = 5</me></p>
        <p><alert>(d)</alert> <m>(x - 3)^2 + (y - 10)^2 = 25</m></p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> Check <m>P(2,3)</m> is outside: <m>1 + 49 = 50 > 25</m> ✓
          (a vertex of the square is outside the inscribed circle).</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2022 Q2(b) — Two touching circles -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-touching-2022">
      <title>LC 2022, Q2(b) — Touching Circles</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Circles <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> touch at <m>(12, 11)</m>.
          Circle <m>s</m> has centre <m>(22, 13)</m>.
          (i) Find another point on <m>s</m>.
          (ii) The radius of <m>t</m> is half that of <m>s</m>. Find the centre of <m>t</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><alert>(i)</alert> The point <m>(12, 11)</m> is on <m>s</m>. The diametrically
          opposite point: reflect <m>(12, 11)</m> through centre <m>(22, 13)</m>:
          <me>(2(22) - 12,\; 2(13) - 11) = (32, 15)</me></p>
        <p><alert>(ii)</alert> <em>Calculate</em> the radius of <m>s</m>:
          <me>r_s = \sqrt{(22-12)^2 + (13-11)^2} = \sqrt{100 + 4} = \sqrt{104}</me>
          <m>r_t = \frac{r_s}{2}</m>. Since the circles touch externally at <m>(12, 11)</m>,
          the centre of <m>t</m> is on the line from <m>(22, 13)</m> through <m>(12, 11)</m>,
          at distance <m>r_t</m> on the far side of <m>(12, 11)</m>.</p>
        <p>Direction from <m>s</m>'s centre to touch point: <m>(12-22, 11-13) = (-10, -2)</m>.
          Continue half that distance beyond the touch point:
          <me>\text{Centre of } t = (12 - 5,\; 11 - 1) = (7, 10)</me></p>
        <p><alert>Verify:</alert> Distance from <m>(7, 10)</m> to <m>(12, 11)</m>:
          <m>\sqrt{25 + 1} = \sqrt{26} = \frac{\sqrt{104}}{2}</m> ✓.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2025 Q3(a) — Matching circles to equations -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-match-2025">
      <title>LC 2025, Q3(a) — Visual Matching</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Three circles <m>p</m>, <m>q</m>, <m>r</m> are shown on a diagram.
          Match each to: <m>x^2 + y^2 = 9</m>, <m>(x-6)^2 + (y-2)^2 = 4</m>,
          <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>Identify</em> centre and radius of each equation:</p>
        <p><m>x^2 + y^2 = 9</m>: centre <m>(0,0)</m>, radius <m>3</m> → large circle at origin = <m>q</m>.</p>
        <p><m>(x-6)^2 + (y-2)^2 = 4</m>: centre <m>(6,2)</m>, radius <m>2</m> → small circle at right = <m>r</m>.</p>
        <p><m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m>: centre <m>(0,0)</m>, radius <m>1</m> → tiny circle at origin = <m>p</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <!-- ======================================================== -->
  <!-- SUBSECTION 8: Axis Tangency / Geometric Reasoning         -->
  <!-- ======================================================== -->

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-circ-ps-axis-tangent">
    <title>Axis Tangency and Geometric Reasoning</title>

    <!-- 2024 Q4(c) — Lowest point + y-axis tangent -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-lowest-2024">
      <title>LC 2024, Q4(c)</title>
      <statement>
        <p><m>(2, 1)</m> is the lowest point on circle <m>s</m>.
          The <m>y</m>-axis is tangent to <m>s</m>.
          Find the radius and centre.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><alert>Step 1:</alert> <em>Appreciate</em> "lowest point" means the centre is
          directly above: <m>h = 2</m>, <m>k = 1 + r</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 2:</alert> <m>y</m>-axis tangent means <m>|h| = r</m>, so <m>r = 2</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 3:</alert> <m>k = 3</m>. Centre <m>= (2, 3)</m>, radius <m>= 2</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Step 4:</alert> Lowest point: <m>(2, 3-2) = (2,1)</m> ✓.
          Distance to <m>y</m>-axis: <m>2 = r</m> ✓.
          The <m>y</m>-axis tangent point is <m>(0, 3)</m> — the point on the diameter
          directly opposite the rightmost point <m>(4, 3)</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2025D Q2(b) — Centre on x-axis, tangent square -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-axis-centre-2025d">
      <title>LC 2025D, Q2(b)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Circle <m>k</m> has centre on the <m>x</m>-axis and contains <m>O(0,0)</m>
          and <m>T(4,0)</m>. (i) Find centre and equation.
          (ii) Square <m>PQRS</m> has all sides tangent to <m>k</m>. Find the area.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>(i) Centre on <m>x</m>-axis: <m>k = 0</m>. Midpoint of <m>O</m> and <m>T</m>:
          <m>h = 2</m>. Radius <m>= 2</m>.
          <m>(x-2)^2 + y^2 = 4</m>.</p>
        <p>(ii) Tangent square has side <m>= 2r = 4</m>.
          Area <m>= 16</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <!-- ======================================================== -->
  <!-- SUBSECTION 9: Circumference and Area                      -->
  <!-- ======================================================== -->

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-circ-ps-circ-area">
    <title>Circumference, Area, and Measurement</title>

    <!-- 2023 Q5 — Inscribed and circumscribed -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-inscribed-2023">
      <title>LC 2023, Q5</title>
      <statement>
        <p>A square has sides 12 cm. Circle <m>c</m> is inscribed (touches all sides).
          Circle <m>k</m> is circumscribed (passes through all corners).
          (a) Radius of <m>c</m>. (b) Area of <m>c</m>. (c) Percentage of square.
          (d) Show radius of <m>k \approx 8.49</m>. (e) Circumference of <m>k</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>(a) Inscribed circle diameter = side: <m>r_c = 6</m> cm.</p>
        <p>(b) <m>A_c = \pi(6)^2 = 36\pi \approx 113.10</m> cm<m>{}^2</m>.</p>
        <p>(c) <m>\dfrac{113.10}{144} \times 100 \approx 79\%</m>.</p>
        <p>(d) Circumscribed circle diameter = diagonal:
          <m>d = \sqrt{12^2 + 12^2} = 12\sqrt{2} \approx 16.97</m>.
          <m>r_k = 8.49</m> cm ✓.</p>
        <p>(e) <m>C_k = 2\pi(8.49) \approx 53.34</m> cm.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- 2018 Q5 — Rotating wheels -->
    <example xml:id="ex-circ-ps-wheels-2018">
      <title>LC 2018, Q5(b) — Rotating Wheels</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Wheel <m>u</m> has radius 4 cm, wheel <m>v</m> has radius 6 cm.
          They are in non-slip contact.
          (i) Find each circumference in terms of <m>\pi</m>.
          (ii) If <m>v</m> makes 100 rotations, how many does <m>u</m> make?</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>(i) <m>C_u = 8\pi</m> cm, <m>C_v = 12\pi</m> cm.</p>
        <p>(ii) Non-slip means equal arc length.
          <m>v</m> travels <m>100 \times 12\pi = 1200\pi</m> cm.
          <m>u</m> rotations: <m>\dfrac{1200\pi}{8\pi} = 150</m>.</p>
        <p><alert>Analyse:</alert> The smaller wheel always turns more times — makes sense. ✓</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

